{
  "texts": [
    "This allows for the calculation of an additive effect, which is simply the sum of the individual effects at a given dose.",
    "If the combined experiments are carried out in concentrations with dose x i, we have according to Loewe Additivity principle: X 1, …, X n represent the doses applied to the drugs within individual experiments, while E stands for the resultant effect (Goldoni and Johansson 2007).",
    "The mentioned combination involves fractions of individual doses that achieve the effect separately.",
    "When these fractions are added together, they sum up to one and result in the same effect (Lederer et al. 2019).",
    "To make this concept clearer imagine two substances: compound A and compound B."
  ]
}